tip.text:
Take yourself to the quaint village that is Clapton, give your moustache a good twirl and then squeeze your bum into a seat in this wee crÃªperie - or if the weather is nice come find us amongst the lavender outback. Now listen carefully dearies; the menu is broken up into crÃªpes and galettes. Galettes are made with buckwheat flour, water and salt - nothing else, which makes them crunchy and a little nutty to taste. They are then topped with all manner of proper French goodies, from homemade ratatouille and blue cheese sauce to Bayonne ham with sautÃ©ed potatoes and Reblochon (one of the smelliest of the cheeses).

The list of crepes is - we are pleased to say - almost as long as the savouries. Standouts are flambÃ©ed pear, chocolate sauce and vanilla ice cream or if you're feeling a little fancy try the sugar, fresh orange and lemon juice with a generous swig of Grand Marnier. Ooft yes please Mr French guy!

When the moon hits your eye like a big pizza pie, thaaaat's amooore... and when you squeeze into a little no-frills pizzeria and eat some of the good stuff straight from a wood-fired oven that's amore too. Poetto in Hackney offers just that, simple honest pizza goodness, priced most favourably and topped with all the love in the world.

Toppings range from mortadella, burrata, and pistachio to parma ham and parmesan, so yeah it's all the classics done to a T. There's also a few salads and a couple of shellfish-heavy pasta dishes on the menu: nothing too wild just good old-fashioned holiday-feeling food. Add craft beer and Italian wine, and you'll have a frightfully good time.

The sun will never set on the London chippie with places like Sutton & Sons flying the salt and vinegar flag. This place is a step up from your standard take away, without getting all snooty. They use the fishmongers across the road so things are always fresh, they brew their own beer, and the batter is a crispy masterpiece. You can even get moules mariniÃ¨re if you want to get all continental. Just save room for the puddings.

Chicken shops are a dime a dozen in London, but there's one newcomer that's cornered a fresh angle - House of Hackney (used to be called House of Seitan), with their vegan fried chicken and classic chip shop sides, completely blew up social media as they opened their doors for hoards of hungry herbivores.

Cheekily situated next to a butcher's shop (and with queues that put that butcher's shop to shame), the Seitan "chicken" lives up to the real thing, albeit much more bird friendly (and a little pricier) than your OG chicken and chips. Whether you're a flexitarian, participating in Veganuary, or stay meat-free year round, it's nice to know that you can now indulge in your favourite comfort food without compromising your morals.

We all need that dependable, cheap Middle Eastern joint 'round the corner: giving you a bit of nutritional support when times are tough and times are tiring. Anatolia Ockabasi is just that spot for all of that, beating off some very mixed competition on Mare Street with a nice selection of grilled meats, mezes and pides. A huge big charcoal grill dominates this place and it's a mesmerising sight to see it in action.

This is a no-frills kind of place and that's really how we like our kebabies. Kebabies? Have we just coined something weird and wonderful? Hmm. Our picks include the lamb kofte, the moussaka or the hot mixed meze but really, it's all pretty good. A sensible option if you fancy something tasty but don't want to spend big.

An unassuming restaurant on a quiet stretch of Mare street, Tre Viet is serving up simple, delicious Vietnamese fare on the cheap.

The mural-adorned walls and bamboo-latticed ceiling, complete with hanging lanterns, are so kitsch they come off cosy and charming - and once a steaming bowl of pho is placed in front of you, with the fragrant scents of lemongrass, coriander, and garlic wafting up your nose hole, youâll be transported straight to the Mekong delta. We'd also recommend any of their sizzling stir frys, just donât be afraid to go in the with the lime, chilli, and sauces on the table - flavour it up, baby.

The âbest pizza in Londonâ debate is never gonna die, but letâs get it straight - Sodo is frickinâ dope pizza. Theyâve spread out their dough in East but this is their original HQ: a cosy cubbyhole nestled along Upper Clapton Road thatâs all worn woods, greenery, and sumptuous sourdough pies suitably thin, topping-heavy and oozing with flavour.

Combining fresh ingredients, weâd tip either the veggie friendly Lorena (tomato, mozzarella, butternut squash, feta, pine nuts and rosemary) or the less veggie friendly Wicker Man (tomato, mozzarella, 'ndjua, pepperoni, mascarpone and scotch bonnet honey). Capable of being the casual pizzeria for something low key or the date night spot when a lil' romance is needed, itâs an excellent pizza place to drop in on.

On first inspection this seriously low-key spot feels like it might not have long left on this plot of uber hot Broadway Market retail space, but poke your head inside and youâll find a strong contingent of dedicated followers. Maybe itâs because there is a gap in the market round here for no-frills cafe; maybe itâs the lack of any discernible pretension; or maybe itâs the cheap-as-chips gÃ¶zleme, made fresh to order in the window and served steaming and flaky as hell (hell is probably flaky right?). Whatever it is, we like it. When the property developers inevitably rear their heads, weâll be first on the picket line.

How can such good pizza be served up so quickly, and so cheaply? It's freakish. Franco Manca has leapt on to most people's 'top pizzas in London' lists, and we straight up applaud this. Their Neapolitan-style pizzas are made with sourdough that's been left to rise for 20 hours minimum, and are crispy, chewy things of wonder.

Their menu is plenty versatile too - you can choose how thick you want your chorizo sliced, there's a daily specials menu, and a nice little wine and beer selection.

A Broadway Market hotspot, La Bouche is the kind of artisan, bougie deli and cafe that's busy whatever time of day you rock up there. It makes you wonder whether people ever actually leave London Fields for work. We reckon not. There are people looking busy on laptops, people chatting over cappuccinos and people sitting out on the prime real estate pavement tables, appearing impossibly cool & relaxed. And don't ever think you'll get a seat out there on a Sunday.

On its packed shelves you'll find all sorts of fancy speciality produce including cheese, veggies, meats, wines, pasta, biscuits and homemade cakes. The kind of food you'll acknowledge as looking delicious, but not quite delicious enough for you to spunk Â£7 on a packet of tortellini. Definitely check out the sandwiches here which are ideal for a cheap eat, coming in at around Â£5 and in a variety of breads - our tip is the duck rillettes with mustard.

We all know that pie & mash and jellied eel are fundamental to the traditional cockney lifestyle. So, even if the thought of the latter makes your tummy wriggle, it's worth knowing that there are few East London spots more authentic than F. Cooke for such a treat.

With the decor seemingly unchanged since the... well ages ago, along with the food, there's a certain comfort in knowing that what you're eating is a tried and tested formula that has pleased many a grandad and geezer over the years. Oh, and mash don't come much better than this.

Mangal 1 is proof that the holy kebab is not solely reserved for drunken gluttony. This ocakbasi is a king among London's many kebab houses, and maybe the best is Dalston (which is saying something). Nudge your way past the people waiting by the door for takeaway, past the gargantuan, smoking grill and find a table in the crowded dining room.

Service is brusque at best, but you're here for food, not service, so grab the attention of a waiter and order up. Starters are tasty but unnecessary - the grill is where it's at. Ideally you're in a group large enough to warrant a big platter where you can sample a range of perfectly grilled meats. If you're riding solo, go for the lamb chops. Either way you'll get fluffy, warm bread, salads and some sauces. It's byob, so run over the road for beers and then get stuck into your meat feast. Just leave some room for the hella syrupy baklava, ok?

The amount of great Turkish joints along this stretch of road between Dalston and Stoke Newington means that to stand out you gotta be doing some special. And thatâs exactly what Cirrik is doing. Now, if youâre expecting polished decor, attentive service, or a quiet meal, weâd suggest shedding those hopes asap, because they wonât be satisfied. What will be satisfied, however, is that rumbling noise coming from your belly.

Cirrik makes a real strong start to proceedings, from the seductive smells of meats grilling on the charcoal, the light, puffy bread which carries all the meaty, oniony goodness all the way to the complementary izgara sogan (grilled onions with pomegranate). They know how to get people salivating. The treats continue throughout the meal, though, with the delicately crispy pides and the tender, superbly spiced adana kebab being our humble recommendations.

If youâre just looking for something quick and cheap, you really canât do better than their lahmacun which is fragrant, rich and filling, all for a measly two quid (three if you eat in).

This no-nonsense, no-frills spots serves up all kinds of sweet and savoury delights at seriously reasonable prices. After introducing yourself to the local characters that tend to frequent, tuck in to a mighty fine bagel, a glistening pink donut or a slice of your cake of choice. The joy of this place is that it is just as rad at 4 in the am after a heavy one as it is at 8 in the am before work. The world would be a better place with more 24 hour bakeries, in our humble opinion.

House prices must be rocketing in Stokey with all the UK's Best Kebab Awards being snapped up in the ends (feeling proud). This kebabery took home the top prize in 2017 and their high standards still remain at the top. Open seven days a week till 2am, you can always rely on this prima doner to help soak up that booze.

Whilst their juicy kebabs take centre stage, their falafels and burgers play strong supporting roles too - so hunker down for some good feasting.

When the trend of tarting up street food continues, who are we to get in its way? After popping up here and there, the cheekily named Fanny's has opened its first brick and mortar site up in Stokey.

Kebabs arrive filled with either chicken, lamb, halloumi or falafel and are freshened up with chilli sauce, spiced yoghurt, pickles and crunchy slaw. Yep that sounds like something you might quite like, doesn't it deary? Sides are hella saucy too - think harissa wings, Persian fries or baba ganoush and flatbread. You can even get the goods over rice, salad or in a gf wrap. Grab a stool, munch your way through, then get outa there. It's fast food - but pimped.

This is just the type of no-frills, no-fancies cafe you're looking for when you need a cheap and filling eat. Evin Cafe offers a vast array of Mediterranean and English grub come day or night, with hefty portions making pretty good value for money, albeit from a pool of pretty standard cafe classics. Sometimes, we're okay with that.

With Turkish coffee that'll put hair on your chest; kebabs of every variery; and tasty gÃ¶zleme whipped up by skilled Turkish ladies at the front, this suits many a feeding need. Though we would not recommend going for a dessert.

Pizza and frozen margaritas - was there ever a finer match made in heaven? Voodoo Ray's is at its prime at 2 in the morning when a sloppy slice of the good stuff is just what you need. Pizza is sold by the slice and margaritas are sold out of those cool Slush Puppy machines.

Letâs get it straight - this is frickin' dope pizza. Sodo were once just Clapton cult heroes but they've spread a little and their Bethnal Green joint, hidden far from the madding crowds on a quiet cobbled street in a railway arch, gives their beautifully thin, topping-heavy, sumptuous sourdough pies ample space for expression.

Keeping things strictly pizza, we came in and went in on the Lorena (tomato, mozzarella, butternut squash, feta, pine nuts and rosemary); and the Wicker Man (tomato, mozzarella, 'ndjua, pepperoni, mascarpone and scotch bonnet honey). One was sweet; one savoury - both surprised us with interesting combos of fresh ingredients that managed to keep it classic whilst also offering something fresh. The space itself, rife with plants, soft woods and supple lighting, hits the perfect note of a casual pizzeria capable of evolving into something romantic and amorous given the right occasion. An excellent pizza place to drop in on.

A glossy pic of this unique oasis is what youâll find when you look up the words âpureâ, âmagicâ and âheart-warmingly beautifulâ in the Dojo dictionary. Yeah, our dictionary has pictures. Sitting on the old Eastern Curve railway line, entering the covert door here is akin to walking through the wardrobe to Narnia - minus the talking animals, mythical creatures and foreboding sense of danger. Instead youâve got plants, wood-chippings, fairy lights and a friendly crowd of locals basking in Dalstonâs version of heaven.

The long, curved garden features plants, veggies and herbs; a cafe that also sells beers, wine and homemade soups; a stage for live music; and a pizza oven doing Â£6 pies. This is truly a community place with a wealth of programmes and workshops aimed at helping isolated people. Chilling with some pals beneath the tree-top canopy as the evening draws in is one of Londonâs true pleasures.
